<section xml:id="sec-semisimple-modules" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Semisimple modules</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this section we assume that <m>R</m> is a commutative ring with unity and <m>A</m> is a right <m>R</m>-algebra. For a right <m>A</m>-module <m>M</m> we denote by <m>S(M)</m> the collection of all <m>A</m>-submodules of <m>M</m>. We follow <xref ref="bib-Jacobson-II"/> and <xref ref="bib-Pierce"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Recall the definition of semisimple module (see <xref ref="def-semisimple-module"/>), viz., a right <m>A</m>-module <m>M</m> is semisimple if <m>M</m> is a direct sum of simple right <m>A</m>-modules.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-complement-of-a-submodule">
        <title>Complement of a submodule</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Assume that <m>R</m> is a commutative ring with unity and <m>A</m> is a right <m>R</m>-algebra. Let <m>M</m> be a right <m>A</m>-module and <m>P,N\leq M</m> be <m>A</m>-submodules of <m>M</m>. The module <m>P</m> is called a <em>complement</em> of <m>N</m> in <m>S(M)</m> if <m>M=P\oplus N</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def-independent-submodules">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>S=\{N_i\}_{i\in I}</m> be a collection of submodules of <m>M</m>. The set <m>S</m> is said to be <em>independent</em> if for every <m>N_i\in S</m> we have
                <me>
                    N_i\cap \sum_{N_k\neq N_i}N_k=0.
                </me>
                Otherwise we call <m>S</m> <em>dependent</em>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def-direct-sum-of-modules">
        <title>Internal direct sum</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>M=\sum_{j\in J}N_j</m> is a right <m>A</m>-module. If <m>S=\{N_j\}_{j\in J}</m> is independent then, <m>M</m> is called a <em>internal direct sum of submodules</em> <m>N_j</m>, and we write it as <m>M=\bigoplus_{j\in J}N_j</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-universal-property-of-direct-sum">
        <title>Direct sum - Existence and universal property</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>S=\{M_j\}_{j\in J}</m> be a nonempty collection of right <m>A</m>-modules. There exists a right <m>A</m>-module <m>M</m> with <m>A</m>-module homomorphisms <m>i_j\colon M_j\to M</m> for every <m>j\in J</m>, and with the following universal property: if there exists a right <m>A</m>-module <m>N</m> with <m>f_j\colon M_j\to N</m> for every <m>j\in J</m> then there exists a unique <m>A</m>-module homomorphism <m>f\colon M\to N</m> such that <m>f\circ i_j=f_j</m> for each <m>j\in J</m>. 
            </p>
<!--                <figure xml:id="fig-universal-property-of-direct-sum">
               <caption>Universal property of direct sum</caption>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzcd}
                        M_j\arrow[rd,"i_j"]\arrow[rdd,"f_j",bend right]\amp\amp M_k\arrow[ld,"i_k"]\arrow[ldd,"f_k",bend left]\\
                        \amp M\arrow[d,"f",dashed]\amp\\
                        \amp N\amp
                        \end{tikzcd}    
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>-->
        </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
        We show in this section that semisimple modules (see <xref ref="def-semisimple-module"/>) are characterized by existence of complements of its submodules. We begin with the following lemma.
    </p> 
    <lemma xml:id="lem-step-in-charaterization-of-semisimple-modules">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M=\sum_{j\in J}N_j</m>, where <m>N_j</m> is a simple <m>A</m>-submodule of <m>M</m>. If <m>P\leq M</m> then, there exists <m>I\subseteq J</m> such that
                <me>
                    M=\left(\bigoplus_{i\in I}N_i\right)\bigoplus P.
                </me>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Consider the following set.
            <me>\Sigma=\left\{\{N_i\}_{i\in I}\cup\{P\}:\sum_{i\in I}N_i+P=\left(\bigoplus_{i\in I} N_i\right)\bigoplus P\text{ for some subset }I\subseteq J\right\}</me>
            The set <m>\Sigma\neq\emptyset</m> as empty sum of submodules is considered as <m>\{0\}</m>. Suppose that we have a chain of submodules corresponding to a chain of subsets <m>\{I_{k}\}</m> of <m>J</m>. Then, put <m>I=\cup I_k</m>. We claim that <me>\sum_{i\in I}N_i+P=\left(\bigoplus_{i\in I}N_i\right)\bigoplus P.</me> For any <me>\sum_{r=1}^sn_{i_r}+p\in \sum_{t\in I_k}N_t+P=\left(\bigoplus_{t\in I_k}N_t\right)\bigoplus P\text{ for some }k.</me>
            This shows that every chain has an upper bound. By Zorn's lemma there exists a maximal element, say a subset <m>I\subseteq J</m> such that <m>\sum_{i\in I}N_i+P=\left(\bigoplus N_i\right)\bigoplus P</m>. Put <m>M_1=\sum_{i\in I}N_i+P</m>. By maximality of <m>I</m>, <m>M_1\cap N_j\neq 0</m> for every <m>j\in J</m>. As <m>N_j</m> is simple, we must have <m>M_1\cap N_j=N_j</m>, i.e., <m>N_j\subseteq M_1</m> for each <m>j\in J</m>. Therefore, we get the result.
        </p>
    </proof>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-sum-of-simple-modules-is-direct-sum">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M=\sum_{j\in J} N_j</m>, where <m>N_j</m> are simple right <m>A</m>-modules. Then, there exists <m>I\subseteq J</m> such that <m>M=\bigoplus_{i\in I}N_i</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <proof>
        <p>
            This follows by taking <m>P</m> as the zero module in <xref ref="lem-step-in-charaterization-of-semisimple-modules"/>.
        </p>
    </proof>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-semisimple-implies-existence-of-complement">
        <title>Existence of complement for semisimple modules</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M</m> be a semisimple right <m>A</m>-module, and <m>P\leq M</m>. Then there exists <m>N\leq M</m> such that <m>M=N\bigoplus P</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <proof>
        <p>
            This is a direct consequence of <xref ref="def-semisimple-module"/> and <xref ref="lem-step-in-charaterization-of-semisimple-modules"/>
        </p>
    </proof>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-existence-of-complement-for-submodules">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M</m> be a right <m>A</m>-module with the following property.
                <men xml:id="eqn-complement-property">
                    \text{For any submodule }N\leq M\text{ there exists a submodule }N'\leq M\text{ such that }M=N\oplus N'
                </men>
                Then, for any submodule <m>L\leq M</m> has the above property <xref ref="eqn-complement-property"/>, i.e., for any submodule <m>P\leq L</m> there exists <m>Q\leq L</m> such that <m>L=P\oplus Q</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Let <m>P\leq L</m>. Then, there exists <m>P'\leq M</m> such that <m>M=P\oplus P'</m>. Note that <m>L=P\oplus (P'\cap L)</m>. Indeed, <m>P\cap\left(P'\cap L\right)\subseteq P\cap P'=0</m>, and for <m>\ell\in L</m> there exists unique <m>p\in P</m> and <m>p'\in P'</m> such that <m>\ell=p+p'</m>, i.e., <m>p'=\ell-p\in L</m> and hence, <m>p'\in L\cap P'</m> and <m>L=P+(L\cap P')</m>.
        </p>
    </proof>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-existence-of-complement-implies-existence-of-simple-submodule">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>M</m> be a nonzero right <m>A</m>-module with the property that every <m>A</m>-submodule of <m>M</m> has a complement in <m>M</m>. Then, <m>M</m> has a simple <m>A</m>-submodule.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Suppose that <m>0\neq m\in M</m>. Consider the following set.
            <me>
                \Sigma=\left\{N\leq M:m\not\in N\right\}
            </me>
            As <m>0\in\Sigma</m>, the set <m>S\neq\emptyset</m>. Furthermore, by considering a partial order given by inclusion of sets, every chain in <m>S</m> has an upper bound, viz., the union of sets in the chain. By Zorn's lemma, there exists a maximal element, say <m>P\in S</m>. Note that <m>P\neq M</m>. By the assumption on <m>M</m> there exists <m>P'\leq M</m> such that <m>M=P\oplus P'</m>. The module <m>P'</m> is a candidate for a simple submodule. First note that <m>P'\neq 0</m> because <m>P\neq M</m>. Suppose that <m>m=p+x</m> for uniquely determined <m>p\in P</m> and <m>x\in P'</m>. As <m>m\not\in P</m>, we must have <m>x\neq 0</m>. We show that any two nonzero submodules of <m>P'</m> intersect nontrivially. Take a nonzero submodule <m>L</m> of <m>P'</m>. The submodule <m>P+L</m> contains <m>P</m> properly and hence, <m>m=p+x\in P+L</m> by the maximality of <m>P</m>. However, <m>P+L=P\oplus L</m>, hence <m>x\in L</m>. We thus have shown that every nonzero submodule of <m>P'</m> contains <m>x\neq 0</m>. If <m>Q\leq P'</m> then there exist <m>Q'\leq P'</m> such that <m>P'=Q\oplus Q'</m> by <xref ref="lem-existence-of-complement-for-submodules"/>. However, this implies that submodules <m>Q</m> and <m>Q'</m> have trivial intersection. This is possible only if one of the <m>Q</m> or <m>Q'</m> is trivial and the other one is <m>P'</m>. Hence, <m>P'</m> is simple.
        </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
        We are now in a position to prove the following equivalent characterization of semisimple modules.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-equivalent-conditions-for-semisimple-modules">
        <title>Equivalent conditions for semisimple modules</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                For a right <m>A</m>-module <m>M</m> following conditions are equivalent.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The module <m>M</m> is semisimple;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            There are simple submodules <m>N_j\leq M</m> such that <m>M=\sum_{j\in J}N_j</m>;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The module <m>M\neq 0</m> has the property <xref ref="eqn-complement-property"/>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    <proof>
        <p>
            By the definition of semisimple module we get (1) implies (2).
        </p>
        <p>
            The condition (2) implies the condition (3) follows from <xref ref="lem-step-in-charaterization-of-semisimple-modules"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Now assume (3). By <xref ref="prop-existence-of-complement-implies-existence-of-simple-submodule"/>, <m>M</m> has a simple submodule. Let <m>\{N_j\}_{j\in J}</m> be all simple submodules of <m>M</m>. By the assumption <m>M</m> satisfies <xref ref="eqn-complement-property"/>, i.e., there exists <m>P\leq M</m> such that <m>M=\left(\sum_{j\in J}N_j\right)\oplus P</m>. However, by <xref ref="lem-existence-of-complement-for-submodules"/> and applying <xref ref="prop-existence-of-complement-implies-existence-of-simple-submodule"/> to <m>P</m>, we get that <m>P</m> has a simple submodule. As a simple submodule of <m>P</m> is also a simple submodule of <m>M</m> we get that <m>\left(\sum_{j\in J}N_j\right)\cap P\neq 0</m>, a contradiction. Therefore, we must have <m>M=\sum_{j\in J}N_j</m>. Thus we get (1) by using <xref ref="cor-sum-of-simple-modules-is-direct-sum"/>.
        </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
        As a direct consequence we obtain the following corollary.
    </p>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-quotient-and-submodule-of-semisimple-module-is-semisimple">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>M</m> is a semisimple <m>A</m>-module and <m>N</m> is a proper <m>A</m>-submodule of <m>M</m> then, <m>N</m> and <m>M/N</m> are semisimple <m>A</m>-modules.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Direct sum of semisimple <m>A</m>-modules is a semisimple <m>A</m>-module.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
</section>